And if the top manager is affected, the complaints go directly to the directorate.
"The public opinion court intercepted the power of the inspectors," said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If it turns out that the company is ill-treated or unethical, even if the inspectors do not intervene, the company may face costly consequences in the form of client boycotts, staff outflows and lawsuits, Quinlan informed.
Ruby Tuesday, a network of restaurants where more than 25,000 employees work in 500 institutions, used Convercent for over a year to make sure that staff were aware of the rules and procedures, and to suggest a simple way to approach the company's head office.
