Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent research suggests the opposite: diet, rich in meat proteins and dairy products, can help alleviate symptoms for those suffering from intestinal disease.
This incurable disease, which affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 3,00000 in the United Kingdom, leads to the cradle and grinding of the stomach, the chronic or bloody nose, the loss of weight and extreme fatigue.
Usually, in order to mitigate symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers at the University of Washington found that the main amino acid of the protein triptofan contributes to the production of immunum cells that increase the tolerance of the intestine.
The lead researcher, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that immunized cells in the intestine were being monitored to ensure that harmful microbes from food did not penetrate the body.
Cells capable of launching an inflammation process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance by protecting the body and without harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too severe in the direction of inflammation, it can lead to inflammable intestinal diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice with a certain bacteria in the intestines have increased the tolerance of the cell.
And this bacteria needs a triptofone - one of the building elements of the protein - to start the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between one kind of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is part of a normal microbial intestine, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more triptofan was contained in the power of mice, the more these immune cells they had."
