In Russia, two new areas of advanced socio-economic development - Abasa and Novotroitzk - will emerge.
The relevant decisions of the Government of the Russian Federation will enter into force today, 4 August.
The boundaries and economic activities of the THO have been defined in the territory of the city of Abasa in the Republic of Hakasia.
In a city where 15,000 people live, there will be a special legal regime for business, as well as a minimum level of capital investment for residents, and a minimum number of new permanent jobs.
This is expected to bring about 2.5 billion roubles of investment into the city and to create more than 600 new jobs.
The list of economic activities in which the Abasa TS will have a special legal regime for business, such as crop production, livestock, food production, non-alcohol beverages and clothing.
Already, the Government of the Republic has signed framework agreements for 8 investment projects.
It is also planned to reduce the Territory ' s dependence on the Abakan mine station.
In January 2017, the authorities of the region reported that Hakasia had fulfilled all the conditions of Minegon Development for the establishment of a THO.
Similarly, the authorities of the Orenburg region have done so.
There, the city of Novotroitzk will also have a pre-existing socio-economic development area.
This will allow for the diversification of the monocities economy, reduce its dependence on the Ural Steel Graduation Company, create more than 2.3 thousand jobs and attract investment in more than 8 mm billion rubles.
The list of economic activities in which the new TS will have a special legal regime for entrepreneurs includes, inter alia, freshwater fish production, food production, medicines and medical materials.
Novotroitzk was the first of the monocities in the Orenburg region to become a THO.
We recall that the territory of advanced development is an economic zone with favourable tax conditions, simplified administrative procedures and other privileges that are created to attract investment in improving the lives of the population.
Among the benefits for the residents of the THO are: a profit tax of not more than 5 per cent during the first five years, and at least 10 per cent for the next five years, social contributions of 7.6 per cent over 10 years, the free customs regime, the concessionary regime for connectivity to various infrastructure facilities, and concessional rent rates.
